{"title_page": "Second Jones government", "text_new": "{{Infobox government cabinet\n|cabinet_name       = Second Jones government\n|cabinet_number     = 8th\n|cabinet_type       = [[Welsh Government|devolved government]]\n|jurisdiction       = [[Wales]]\n|flag               = Flag of Wales 2.svg\n|flag_border        = true\n|incumbent          = 2011\u20132016\n|image              = [[File:Carwyn Jones 2011.jpg|100px]]\n|date_formed        = 11 May 2011\n|date_dissolved     = 19 May 2016\n|government_head_title = First Minister\n|government_head    = [[Carwyn Jones]]\n|state_head_title   = Monarch\n|state_head         = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|current_number     = \n|former_members_number = \n|total_number       = \n|political_party    = [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n|legislature_status = [[Minority government|Minority]]\n|opposition_cabinet = \n|opposition_party   = [[Welsh Conservatives]]\n|opposition_leader  = [[Paul Davies (politician)|Paul Davies]] ''Acting'' <br />[[Andrew RT Davies]]\n|election           = \n|last_election      = \n|legislature_term   = [[Members of the 4th National Assembly for Wales|4th National Assembly for Wales]]\n|budget             =\n|incoming_formation = \n|outgoing_formation = \n|previous           = [[First Jones government]]\n|successor          = [[Third Jones government]]\n}}\n\nThe '''second Jones government''' (11 May 2011 \u2013 19 May 2016) was a [[Welsh Labour|Labour]] [[minority government]].\n\nHaving won the largest number of seats in the [[2011 National Assembly for Wales election|2011 general election]] (30 out of 60) the Labour sought to form a minority government, having previously governed in coalition with [[Plaid Cymru]]. [[Carwyn Jones]] was re-elected [[First Minister for Wales|First Minister]] in May 2011 and continued to serve up to and beyond the 2016 election.\n\nDuring the five years of this government there were two significant reshuffles (March 2013 and September 2014) as well as two departures from the Cabinet, both of which led to widespread changes in personnel and in ministerial titles and responsibilities.\n\nThis government was the first since the [[2011 Welsh devolution referendum|2011 referendum]] on primary law making powers and thus passed the first Welsh Law without the expressed consent of Westminster. The Welsh Government under Carwyn Jones also purchased and nationalised [[Cardiff Airport]] during this period.\n\n== Cabinet ==\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1em; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaaaaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; \"\n!|| Name|| Party || Image || Office(s) || Dates(s) (in this government)\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''Rt. Hon [[Carwyn Jones]] AM'''\n|[[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n|[[File:Carwyn Jones 2011.jpg|100px]]\n|'''[[First Minister for Wales|First Minister]]'''\n|13 May 2011 \u2013 19 May 2016 \n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Jane Hutt]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[File:Jane Hutt.jpg|100px]]\n|'''[[Minister for Finance (Wales)|Minister for Finance]]'''<br />\n'''Minister for Finance and Leader of the House'''\n|13 May 2011 \u2013 11 September 2014 <br /> 11 September 2014 - 19 May 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Edwina Hart]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[File:Edwina Hart.jpg|100px]]\n| '''Minister for Business, Enterprise, Technology & Science''' <br />'''Minister for Economy, Science and Transport'''<ref>Including Agriculture, Fisheries and Food 8 July 2014 - 11 September 2014</ref> \n| 13 May 2011- 8 March 2013 <br />8 March 2013 \u2013 19 May 2016  \n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Leighton Andrews]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[File:Leighton Andrews.jpg|100px]]\n| '''[[Department for Education and Skills (Wales)|Minister for Education and Skills]]''' <br />'''Minister for Public Services'''\n| 13 May 2011 - 25 June 2013 <br />11 September 2014 - 19 May 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Lesley Griffiths]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[File:Lesley Griffiths.jpg|100px]]\n| '''Minister for Health and Social Services''' <br />'''Minister for Local Government and Government Business''' <br />'''Minister for Communities and Tackling Poverty'''\n| 13 May 2011 \u2013 14 March 2013<br />14 March 2013 \u2013 11 September 2014<br />11 September 2014 \u2013 19 May 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Mark Drakeford]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[File:Mark Drakeford - National Assembly for Wales.jpg|100px]]\n| '''Minister for Health and Social Services'''\n| 14 March 2013 - 19 May 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Huw Lewis]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[File:Huw Lewis.jpg|100px]]\n| '''Minister for Housing Regeneration & Heritage''' <br />'''Minister for Education and Skills'''\n| 13 May 2011 - 26 June 2013 <br />26 June 2013 - 19 May 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Jeff Cuthbert|Jeffery Cuthbert]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[image:Jeffrey Cuthbert.jpg|100px]]\n| '''Minister for Communities and Tackling Poverty'''\n| 26 June 2013 - 11 September 2014\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Carl Sargent]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[File:Carl Sargeant.jpg|100px]]\n| '''Minister for Local Governmnet and Communities '''<br /> '''Minister for Natural Resources'''\n| 13 May 2011 - 11 September 2014 <br /> 11 September - 19 May 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Alun Davies (politician)|Alun Davies]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[File:Alun Davies.jpg|100px]]\n| '''Natural Resources and Food '''\n| 14 March 2013 - 8 July 2014\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[John Griffiths (Welsh politician)|John Griffiths]] AM'''\n| [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n| [[File:John Griffiths.jpg|100px]]\n| '''Minister for Environment and Sustainable Development'''<br /> '''Minister for Culture and Sport'''\n| 13 May 2011 - 14 March 2013 <br /> 14 March 2013 - 11 September 2014\n|-\n|-\n| colspan=6 style=\"text-align:left\"|<center>'''Office holders given special provisions to attend Cabinet'''</center> \n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Janice Gregory]] AM'''\n|[[Welsh Labour|Labour]]|\n|[[File:Janice Gregory.jpg|100px]]\n|'''[[Chief Whip]]'''\n|2011-2016\n|-\n!  \n|'''Theodore Huckle QC'''<ref>Not an Assembly Member, nominee of the First Minister, approved by AMs</ref>\n|[[Welsh Labour|Labour]] <ref>Member of the Labour Government</ref>\n|[[File:Theodore Huckle QC.jpeg|100px]]\n|'''[[Counsel General for Wales]]'''\n|2011-2016\n|-\n|}\n\n== Junior Ministers ==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1em; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaaaaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; \"\n!|| Name|| Party || Image || Office(s) || Dates(s) (in this government)\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Gwenda Thomas]] AM'''\n|[[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n|[[File:Gwenda Thomas.jpg|100px]]\n|'''Deputy Minister for Children & Social Services'''\n|13 May 2011 \u2013 11 September 2014 \n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Vaughan Gething]] AM'''\n|[[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n|[[File:Vaughan Gething.jpg|100px]]\n|'''Deputy Minister for Tackling Poverty''' <br /> '''Deputy Minister for Health'''\n|26 June 2013 - 11 September 2014 <br /> 11 September 2014 - 19 May 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Ken Skates]] AM'''\n|[[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n|[[File:Ken Skates 2016.jpg|100px]]\n|'''Deputy minister for Skills and Technology''' <br /> '''Deputy Minister for Culture, Sport and Tourism '''\n|26 June 2013 - 11 September 2014 <br /> 11 September 2014 - 19 May 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Rebecca Evans (politician)|Rebecca Evans]] AM'''\n|[[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n|[[File:Rebecca Evans AM (27555062324).jpg|100px]]\n|'''Deputy Minister for Agriculture and Fisheries'''<br /> '''Deputy Minister for Farming and Food'''\n|8 July 2014 \u2013 11 September 2014  <br /> 11 September 2014 - 19 May 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Julie James]] AM'''\n|[[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n|[[File:Julie James - National Assembly for Wales.jpg|100px]]\n|'''Deputy Minister for Skills and Technology'''\n|11 September 2014 \u2013 19 May 2016 \n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Welsh Labour/meta/color}}; width: 1px\" |\n|'''[[Jeff Cuthbert]] AM'''\n|[[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n|[[File:Jeffrey Cuthbert.jpg|100px]]\n|'''Deputy Minister for Skills ''' <br /> '''Deputy Minister for Skills and Technology'''\n|13 May 2011 -14 March 2013 <br /> 14 March 2013 - 26 June 2013\n|}\n\n== Changes ==\n\nA significant reshuffle occurred on 8 March 2013, in which [[Mark Drakeford]] entered the cabinet as Health Minister.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Drakeford new health minister|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-21789790\n|website=BBC News|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the resignation of Leighton Andrews from the cabinet in June 2103 <ref>{{cite web|title=Welsh government reshuffle: Education Minister Leighton Andrews resigns in schools row|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-23056173|website=BBC News|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> Jeff Cuthbert was promoted to the cabinet and Vaughan Gething and Ken Skates become junior ministers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Huw Lewis is named Wales education minister|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-23073832|website=BBC News|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlun Davies was sacked from the government on 8 July 2014, his responsibilities were temporarily restructured with some going to [[Rebecca Evans (politician)|Rebecca Evans]] who joined the government as a junior minister.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welsh Government - Written Statement - Ministerial Responsibilities|url=https://beta.gov.wales/written-statement-ministerial-responsibilities|website=Welsh Government|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> These responsibilities were further altered in a final significant reshuffle occurred on 11 September 2014 where [[Jeff Cuthbert]], [[John Griffiths (Welsh politician)|John Griffiths]] and [[Gwenda Thomas]] all left the government and [[Leighton Andrews]] returned to government while [[Julie James]] became a junior minister.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leighton Andrews rejoins cabinet in reshuffle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-29156951|website=BBC News|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Members of the 4th National Assembly for Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Welsh ministries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones ministry, Second}}\n[[Category:Welsh governments]]\n[[Category:Ministries of Elizabeth II]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:2016 disestablishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Cabinets established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Cabinets disestablished in 2016]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox government cabinet\n|cabinet_name       = Second Jones government\n|cabinet_number     = 8th\n|cabinet_type       = [[Welsh Government|devolved government]]\n|jurisdiction       = [[Wales]]\n|flag               = Flag of Wales 2.svg\n|flag_border        = true\n|incumbent          = 2011\u20132016\n|image              = [[File:Carwyn Jones 2011.jpg|100px]]\n|date_formed        = 11 May 2011\n|date_dissolved     = 19 May 2016\n|government_head_title = First Minister\n|government_head    = [[Carwyn Jones]]\n|state_head_title   = Monarch\n|state_head         = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|current_number     = \n|former_members_number = \n|total_number       = \n|political_party    = [[Welsh Labour|Labour]]\n|legislature_status = [[Minority government|Minority]]\n|opposition_cabinet = \n|opposition_party   = [[Welsh Conservatives]]\n|opposition_leader  = [[Paul Davies (politician)|Paul Davies]] ''Acting'' <br />[[Andrew RT Davies]]\n|election           = \n|last_election      = \n|legislature_term   = [[Members of the 4th National Assembly for Wales|4th National Assembly for Wales]]\n|budget             =\n|incoming_formation = \n|outgoing_formation = \n|previous           = [[First Jones government]]\n|successor          = [[Third Jones government]]\n}}\n\nThe '''second Jones government''' (11 May 2011 \u2013 19 May 2016) was a [[Welsh Labour|Labour]] [[minority government]].\n\nHaving won the largest number of seats in the [[2011 National Assembly for Wales election|2011 general election]] (30 out of 60) the Labour sought to form a minority government, having previously governed in coalition with [[Plaid Cymru]]. [[Carwyn Jones]] was re-elected [[First Minister for Wales|First Minister]] in May 2011 and continued to serve up to and beyond the 2016 election.\n\nDuring the five years of this government there were two significant reshuffles (March 2013 and September 2014) as well as two departures from the Cabinet, both of which led to widespread changes in personnel and in ministerial titles and responsibilities.\n\nThis government was the first since the [[2011 Welsh devolution referendum|2011 referendum]] on primary law making powers and thus passed the first Welsh Law without the expressed consent of Westminster. The Welsh Government under Carwyn Jones also purchased and nationalised [[Cardiff Airport]] during this period.\n\n== Cabinet ==\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1em; background: #f9f9f9; 